<section id="sect-00001">
<title>Learning objectives</title>
<para id="para-00013">By the end of this section you should be able to</para>
<list id="list-00001">
<item>Display output using the print() function.</item>
<item>Obtain user input using the input() function.</item>
</list>
</section>
<section id="sect-00002">
<title>Basic output</title>
<para id="para-00001">The purpose for producing output is to observe what occurs when a program runs. In Python, output is produced with <code class="python inline-code">print(data)</code>. Ex. <code class="python inline-code">print("Today is Monday")</code> will print "Today is Monday" to the screen.</para><para id="para-00002">Two or more data items separated by commas produce a single line of output. Ex. <code class="python inline-code">print("The time is", "8 AM")</code> will print "The time is 8 AM" to the screen on a single line.</para>
<para id="para-00003">By default, <code class="python inline-code">print(data)</code> introduces a new line after the output. <code class="python inline-code">end=</code> is used to avoid a new line after the output. Ex. "The weather for today is sunny!" is printed to the screen on a single line by the following:
<preformat class="python inline-code">print("The weather for today is", end=" ")
print("sunny!")
</preformat></para>
